This confirms not only that some dinosaurs had feathers, a widely accepted theory, but also provides details that fossils cannot, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this bird was chestnut-brown with pale or carotenoid-colored lower edges.
The discovery also sheds light on the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the dinosaur feathers did not have well-developed quill knobs, but did have other feather-like traits—such as branches and twigs—the researchers concluded that the quill knobs were probably a later evolutionary development.
According to the structure of the feathers, it is assumed that they were not used for flight, but more probably for insulation or display. Researchers suggested that the specimen shows a mature plumage and not juvenile down, despite the fact that it is a tail of a young dinosaur.
The researchers have speculated that the specimen shows adult feathers and no juvenile down, despite being a tail of a young dinosaur.
