Thermal images show that there is a variation of temperature between night and day, which suggests that there may be caves.
They are cooler than the surrounding surface, both day and night.
"Their thermal behavior is not as stable as in large caverns on Earth, which often retain a fairly constant temperature, but it is more like those that are deep holes in the ground," said Glen Cushing, a team member of the astrogeology team at the United States Geological Survey and Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, Arizona.
In France, voting traditionally was a technologically simple experience: voters isolate themselves in a booth, put a pre-printed ballot with the indication of their preferred candidate in an envelope.
After the officials verify the identity of the voter, the voter places the envelope in the ballot box and signs the voter list.
French electoral law strictly codifies the process.
Since 1988, polling stations have been required to be transparent, to allow voters and observers to verify that there are no envelopes before the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those of the legally entitled voters.
Kandidati may send representatives to witness every stage of the process. In the evening volunteers count the votes under the watchful eye of observers, according to specific procedures.
