From 1,400 people surveyed before the 2010 federal election, the proportion that opposed Australia becoming a republic increased by 8% from 2008.
Temporary Prime Minister Julia Gillard asserted during the 2010 federal election campaign that she believed Australia should become a republic upon the end of the reign of Queen Elizabeth II.
34% of those in the survey share this view, wishing that Queen Elizabeth II would be the last Australian monarch.
At the extremes of the opinion spectrum, 29 per cent of respondents believe Australia should become a republic as soon as possible, while 31 per cent believe it should never become a republic.
