Under them are larger cats that prey on larger prey in the range of rabbits to antelopes and deer.
Finally, there are many small cats (including stray housecats), which prey on the more abundant insects, rodents, lizards and birds.
The secret of their success is the concept of the niche, the specialty that every cat holds, for which they don’t have to compete with others.
Lions are the most social of all the cats, they live in groups called prides.
A group consists of one to three adult males and several dozen females and offspring.
The women are usually in close kinship with one another, like a large family of sisters and daughters.
Lion prides work very similarly to packs of wolves or dogs, which surprisingly resemble lions (but not other big cats) in behavior, and also very deadly to prey.
A very harmonious athlete, a tiger can climb (although not very well), swim, jump long distances and pull five times stronger than a strong man.
The tiger is in the same genus (Panthera) as the lions, leopards, and jaguars.
The tiger's roar is not like the lion's deep roar, but more like a phrase of harsh, screaming words.
Ocelots are carnivorous and feed on small mammals, snakes, birds, and other small animals.
Scientists believe that ocelots track and find food animals by smell, following the scents on the ground.
They can see well in the dark with their night vision, and are also very stealthy. Ocelots hunt their prey by hiding in the undergrowth and then pouncing.
When a small group of living things (a small population) splits off from the main population from which they came (as when they cross a mountain or a river, or when they move to a new island, so they can not easily return), they often find themselves in an environment different from that in which they were before.
This new environment has other resources and other competitors, so the new population will, to be a strong competitor, have to have other characteristics or adaptations compared to those it had before.
The original population remains the same and the adaptation requirements remain the same.
Over time, as the new population starts to adapt to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
At last, after tens of thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they will not be considered the same species.
We call this process speciation, which simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
Plants produce oxygen that people inhale, and they remove carbon dioxide that people exhale.
Plants produce their food from the sun through photosynthesis and also give shade.
We build our houses from plants and make our clothes from plants. Most of the food we eat is made from plants.
The Mosasaur was the top predator of its time, so it had no natural predators, except for other Mosasaurs.
Its long mandibles were equipped with more than 70 razor-sharp teeth, along with an additional set in its cheek pouch, meaning that nothing that encountered it could escape.
It is not known for certain, but it may have had a bipedal gait. Its diet included turtles, large fish, other mosasaurs, and it may have been a cannibal.
It also attacked anything that entered the water, even a giant dinosaur like the Tyrannosaurus.
