Among the dishes of Ancient Rome there could not be foods that came to Europe from America or Asia in later centuries.
For example, they had no wheat, no tomatoes, no potatoes, no coffee, and no ancient Roman ever tasted a melon.
The Babylonians built a central temple for each of their gods, which was considered the home of the god.
People brought sacrifices to the gods, and the priests tried to meet the needs of the gods by means of rituals and festivals.
Every temple had an open court and an inner sanctum, which was accessible only to priests.
Sometimes special pyramidal towers, called ziggurats, were built as part of the temples.
The top of the tower was a special sanctuary of the god.
In the warm climate of the Middle East the house was not so important.
Most of the life of a Hebrew family took place in the open air.
Women cooked in the courtyard; shops were simply open stalls facing the street. Stone was used to build houses.
In the land of Canaan there were no large forests, so wood was extremely expensive.
