Mohamed was deeply interested in things beyond this mundane life. He used to frequent a cave on the mountain called Noor (light) for contemplation.
The cave itself, which has survived the years, gives a clear idea of the spiritual inclinations of Muhammad.
Located at the top of one of the mountains north of Mecca, the cave is absolutely isolated from the rest of the world.
It is not easy to find, even if you know it exists. When you are in the cave, it is total isolation.
Nothing else can be seen but the bald, beautiful sky above and the many mountains all around. Very little of this world can be seen or heard from within the cave.
The Great Pyramid of Giza is one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World still standing.
Built by the ancient Egyptians in the 3rd century BC, the Great Pyramid is one of the largest pyramid structures ever built to honor a deceased pharaoh.
The Giza plateau, or "Giza Necropolis" in the Egyptian Valley of the Kings contains a few pyramids (including the Great Pyramid, the largest), a few smaller tombs, some temples, and the Great Sphinx.
The Great Pyramid was built to honor Pharaoh Khufu, and among the smaller pyramids, tombs, and temples were built to honor the wives and family members of Khufu.
The "up arrow" mark looks like a V and the "down arrow" mark like a caret or a square without a bottom side.
Up means you start at the top and push the bow, and down means you start at the heel (where your hand is holding the bow) and pull the bow.
The bow up usually produces a more delicate sound, while the bow down is stronger and more firm.
Don't hesitate to add your own marks with a pencil, but remember that the printed marks are there for musical reasons, so they should generally be observed.
The terrified King Louis XVI, Queen Marie Antoinette, their two young children (11-year-old Marie-Thérèse and 4-year-old Louis-Charles), and the sister of the king, Madame Elizabeth, were returned to Paris from Versailles by a mob of market women on 6 October 1789.
They rode to Paris in a carriage, surrounded by a crowd of people, shouting and threatening the king and queen.
The crowd made the king and queen open the windows of the carriage.
For a moment a servant swung the head of a royal guard killed in Versailles before the frightened queen.
The military expenses of the US imperialism in the conquest of the Philippines was paid by the Filipino people.
