The super-profits extracted from the extensive exploitation of the Filipino people constituted the basic income of American imperialism.
To understand the Templars, one must understand the context that helped found the order.
The period during which the events took place is commonly known as the Middle Ages, the period of European history in the 11th, 12th, and 13th centuries (1000–1300).
Before the Middle Ages was the Early Middle Ages and it was followed by the Late Middle Ages, which ended around 1500.
Technological determinism is a term that practically covers a wide range of ideas, from technological push or the technological imperative to a strict sense that human destiny is driven by underlying logic tied to scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a course largely independent of cultural or political influences, and that technology itself has "effects" that are essentially its own, and not socially conditioned.
It could be said that the car leads to the development of roads.
However, a nationwide network is not economically feasible for a small number of cars, so new methods of production are designed to reduce the costs of car ownership.
Mass ownership of cars also leads to a higher incidence of road accidents, which has led to the development of new medical technologies for repairing damaged bodies.
Romanticism had a strong element of cultural determinism, taken up by writers such as Goethe, Fichte and Schlegel.
In the context of Romanticism, the geography molded individuals and over time developed customs and culture related to that geography, and those that were more harmonious with the location of the society were more desirable than arbitrarily imposed laws.
Just as Paris is known as the capital of fashion in the modern world, so Constantinople was considered the fashion capital of feudal Europe.
Its reputation as a center of luxury began around 400 BC and continued until around 1100 BC.
In the 12th century its status had degenerated mainly because the Crusaders had returned with silks and spices considered to be of greater value than those offered by the Byzantine markets.
At that time, the title Capital of Fashion was transferred from Constantinople to Paris.
Gothic style had its peak in the period between the 10th–11th centuries and the 14th century.
The Byzantine culture had a significant influence on the clothing in the East.
However, due to the slow means of communication, styles in the west could lag behind by 25 to 30 years.
By the end of the Middle Ages, Western Europe had begun to develop its own style. One of the major achievements of the period was the use of buttons to fasten clothing as a result of the Crusades.
Subsistence agriculture is agriculture done to produce enough food to meet the needs of the farmer and his/her family.
Subsistence farming is a simple, often organic, system using native seeds for the region with a rotation of crops or other relatively simple techniques to increase yields.
Historically, most farmers were involved in subsistence agriculture and this is still the case in many developing countries.
Subcultures bring together people with similar views who feel marginalized by social norms, and allows them to grow the sense of identity.
Subcultures may be distinguished by age, ethnic affiliation, social class, location and/or gender of members.
The characteristics that determine a subculture as a distinct entity can be linguistic, aesthetic, religious, political, sexual, geographical, or a combination of these factors.
Subcultures often signal their membership with a recognizable and symbolic use of style, which includes fashion, mannerisms, and slang.
One of the most common methods used to illustrate the importance of socialization is to mention a few unfortunate cases of children who, while growing up, due to neglect, bad luck, or malevolent mistreatment, were not socialized by adults.
Such children are called "wild" or feral; some feral children were confined by people (usually their own parents); in some cases such abandonment of a child was due to the rejection of a serious intellectual or physical disability of a child by the parents.
Abandoned children might suffer severe mistreatment or trauma before being left or running away.
Some were said to be raised by animals; others were said to live in the wild.
Rearing only by non-human animals, the feral child shows behavior (within physical limitations) almost entirely similar to that of the nurturing animal, as well as their fear or indifference towards humans.
While project-based learning makes learning more engaging and easier, scaffolding takes it a step further.
Scaffolding is not a learning method, but a tool that provides support to individuals within a new learning experience, such as the use of a new computer program or the beginning of a new project.
Skaffolding can be both virtual and real, in other words, and a teacher is a variant of a scaffold and the small paper clip in Microsoft Office.
Virtual learning environment is embedded in software and has to ask, suggest and explain procedures, which may be difficult for the student to perform on his own.
Children may be placed in foster care for a variety of reasons, ranging from neglect to abuse and even abandonment.
No child should ever have to grow up in a world that is not supportive, nurturing, and educational, but that is what happens.
We view the curator system as a safe haven for such children.
Our system must provide safe homes, loving caregivers, stable education, and reliable healthcare.
The guardian shall provide them with all the necessities which were lacking to them in the house from which they were taken.
The Internet combines elements of both mass and interpersonal communication.
The special features of the Internet add new dimensions to the theory of usage and rewards.
For example, "learning" and "socializing" are suggested as major motives for using the Internet (James et al., 1995).
Eighmey and McCord (1998) also identified "personal involvement" and "continuing relationships" as new persuasive aspects, as they researched responses of the public to websites.
The use of video recording has led to significant discoveries in the interpretation of micro-expressions, facial movements that last a few milliseconds.
Especially it is claimed that it is possible to determine whether a person is lying or not by correctly interpreting micro-expressions.
Oliver Sacks in his article The President's Speech pointed out that people who cannot understand language due to brain damage can still accurately gauge sincerity.
He even suggests that such abilities to interpret human behavior can be shared by animals such as domestic dogs.
Research in the twentieth century has shown that there are two types of genetic variation: hidden and represented.
Mutation adds a new genetic variation, and selection removes it from the pool of visible variation.
Recombination and genetic drift cause the variation to be shuffled back and forth between the two groups in each generation.
In the savannah, it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system, such as that of humans, to satisfy its needs for amino acids from available plants.
Krome, malsukceso fari tion havas gravajn sekvoj: malpliiĝo de kresko, subnutradon kaj finfine morto.
The most readily available resources of plant food would be proteins obtainable from leaves and legumes, but these are difficult to digest for primates like ourselves, unless cooked.
On the other hand, animal-based foods (insects, termites, eggs) are not only easily digestible, but also provide high-quality proteins that contain essential amino acids.
If we consider all the circumstances, we should not be surprised if our ancestors solved their "protein problem" in a similar way to how chimpanzees solve it in the savannah today.
Napping is the process of intentionally falling asleep during your regular sleep period and waking up after a short time (10–60 minutes).
You can easily do this by using a relatively quiet alarm clock to wake up without waking up fully.
If you notice that you are adjusting the clock while you sleep, it can be left on the other side of the room, which will force you to get up to turn it off.
Among other options based on bio-rhythms are drinking a lot of liquid (especially water or tea, a diuretic) before bed, which will make you wake up to urinate.
The extent of inner peace a person has is negatively correlated with the extent of tension in the body and spirit.
The lower the tension, the more positive force there is in life. Every person has the potential to find absolute peace and contentment.
Everyone can achieve illumination. The only obstacle on the path to that goal is your own tension and negativism.
Tibetan Buddhism is based on the teachings of the Buddha, but was extended by the Mahayana path of compassion and by many techniques from Indian yoga.
Buddhism in Tibet is very simple. It consists of Kundalini yoga, meditation and the path of universal love.
In Kundalini yoga, the Kundalini energy (energy of illumination) is awakened by postures, breathing exercises, mantras, and visualizations.
At the heart of Tibetan meditation is the deity yoga. By visualizing various deities, one purifies the energy channels, activates the chakras and creates the illuminated consciousness.
Germany was a common enemy in World War II, leading to cooperation between the Soviet Union and the United States. After the war, a clash of systems, processes and cultures caused the countries to drift apart.
Dva jaroj post the end of the war, the former Allies were now enemies, and the Cold War had begun.
It was to continue for the next 40 years and to have real battles, with proxy armies, on battlefields of Africa to Asia, in Afghanistan, Cuba, and many other places.
By 17 September 1939 the Polish defense was already broken, the only hope being to retreat and reorganize along the Romanian border.
However, these plans were foiled almost overnight, when more than 800,000 soldiers of the Soviet Red Army entered and formed the Belarusian and Ukrainian fronts after an invasion of the eastern regions of Poland, breaking the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact, the Soviet-Polish Non-Aggression Pact, and other bilateral and multilateral international agreements.
Using ships for the transportation of goods is the most efficient way to move large quantities of people and goods across oceans.
The work of a navy traditionally has been to ensure that your country retains the ability to move your people and goods, while preventing your enemy from moving theirs.
The most notable example of this is the North Atlantic Campaign of World War II.
The German Navy, employing U-boats, attempted to stop this traffic.
If the Allies failed, Germany would have been able to conquer Britain as well as the rest of Europe.
Goats were first domesticated around 10,000 years ago in the Zagros Mountains of Iran.
Ancient cultures and tribes began to domesticate them for easy access to milk, wool, meat, and hides.
Domesticated goats were generally kept in flocks that roamed over hills and other pastures, often tended by herders, who were often children or teenagers, similar to the more widely known shepherd.
Railways were built in England from as early as the 16th century.
Although wagonways consisted simply of parallel wooden boards, they allowed horses pulling them to achieve higher speeds and pull heavier loads than on the somewhat rougher roads of the time.
The rails were put in place early enough to allow the tracks to be laid. However, it soon became clear that rails would be more effective if they had an iron strap on top.
This became a popular practice, but iron caused faster wear of the wooden wheels of the wagons.
At the end of the century, wooden wheels were replaced by iron ones. In 1767 the first totally iron rails were presented.
The earliest known mode of transportation was by walking, people began to walk upright around two million years ago with the appearance of Homo erectus (upright man).
Their ancestors, the australopithecines, did not climb as often.
Bipedal specialization is found in fossils of australopithecines dating back to 4.2-3.9 million years ago, although it is likely that the Sahelanthropus went bipedal as early as seven million years ago.
