The world has changed a lot due to scientific and technological achievements of the mankind, and the problems have become much greater due to overpopulation and wasteful way of life of the mankind.
After the Congress approved it on July 4, a handwritten copy signed by Congress president John Hancock and Secretary Charles Thomson was sent to the printing press of John Dunlap, a few blocks away.
During the night, around 150–200 copies were made, known as the Dunlap broadsides.
The first public reading of the document was performed by John Nixon in the courtyard of Independence Hall on July 8.
One was sent on 6 July to George Washington, who read it to his troops in New York on 9 July. A copy arrived in London on 10 August.
The 25 copies of Dunlap that are known to exist are the oldest surviving copies of the document; the original handwritten copy has not survived.
Many paleontologists believe that one group of dinosaurs has survived and lives today. We call them birds.
Many people don't think of them as dinosaurs, because they have feathers and can fly.
But there are many birds that are still similar to dinosaurs.
They have legs with scales and claws, lay eggs and walk on their hind legs, like a dinosaur.
Almost all modern computers are based on processing information that is encoded in the form of binary numbers.
A binary number can have only one of two values, i.e., 0 or 1, and these numbers are called binary digits or bits, using computer jargon.
Internal poisoning can be not immediately apparent. Symptoms such as vomiting are quite general to make a diagnosis impossible.
The best indicator of internal poisoning can be the presence of an open bottle of medication or a toxic household chemical.
