The term chrysalis is formally used by entomologists for this group of insects.
The term is derived from long familiarity with lice, which are insects highly adapted to parasitism of humans.
Both ticks and lice are nidicolous, adapted to living in the nest or lair of their host.
In the United States there are approximately 400,000 known cases of multiple sclerosis (MS), making it the leading neurological disease among young and middle-aged adults.
MS is a disease that affects the central nervous system, which consists of the brain, the spinal cord, and the optic nerve.
Research has shown that women are more likely to get MS than men.
