The fission bomb works on the principle that a nucleus with a large number of protons and neutrons is required.
It is similar to pushing a heavy cart up a hill. Breaking the nucleus releases a little of that energy.
Some atoms have unstable nuclei, which means they tend to break apart with a little or no nudge.
The surface of the Moon consists of rocks and dust. The outer layer of the Moon is called the crust.
The crust is around 70 km thick on the near side and 100 km thick on the far side.
It is thinner under the oceans and thicker under the mountains.
There may be more oceans on the other side, as the crust is thinner.
Content theories focus on discovering what drives or motivates people to act.
These theories suggest that people have certain needs and/or desires that are repressed during maturation to adulthood.
These theories explore what it is about certain people that makes them want to do the things they do, and what things in their environment will make them do or not do certain things.
Two popular content theories are Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs and Herzberg's Two-Factor Theory.
Generally, two behavioral patterns can emerge when administrators start leading their former peers. One end of the spectrum is trying to stay “one of the gang” (or gang).
This type of manager is difficult to make unpopular decisions, performs disciplinary actions, evaluates the effectiveness of work, assigns tasks and requires responsibility from people.
On the other side of the spectrum, you're turning into a completely different person who feels like you need to completely change everything the team has done before and redo it.
The leader is responsible for the success or failure of the team.
This often creates tension between the team leaders and the rest of the team.
Virtual teams follow the same standards of high quality, as traditional teams, but there are subtle differences.
Members of virtual teams often act as a point of contact for their physical group.
They often have more autonomy than members of a traditional team, as their teams can meet at different times, which can be misunderstood by their local managers.
The presence of a true "invisible team" (Larson and LaFasto, 1989, p109) is also a unique component of a virtual team.
The “invisible team” is the administrative team to which each member reports. The invisible team establishes the rules for each member.
Why would an organization want to go through the time-consuming process of establishing a learning organization? One goal for practically applying the concepts of organizational learning is innovation.
When all available resources are effectively used through the functioning departments of an organization, creativity and ingenuity can emerge.
As a result, the process of working together to overcome an obstacle can lead to a new innovative process for serving the needs of clients.
Before an organization can be innovative, leadership must create a culture of innovation and also of shared knowledge and organizational learning.
Angel (2006) explains the Continual Approach as a method used to help organizations achieve a higher level of effectiveness.
Neurobiological data provides physical evidence for a theoretical approach to the study of cognition.
The correlation between brain pathology and behavior keeps scientists to continue the research.
It is a well-known fact that various types of brain damage, trauma, injuries and tumors can affect behavior and change some mental functions.
The progress of new technologies allows us to see and study brain structures and processes that were previously invisible.
This provides us with a lot of information and material to build simulation models that help us understand processes in our mind.
While AI has a strong affinity for science fiction, AI is a significant branch of computer science that is concerned with machine learning and intelligent adaptation.
AI research involves the creation of machines that can perform tasks that typically require human intelligence.
Among examples are checking, planning and scheduling, ability to respond to client diagnoses and questions, and also recognition of handwriting, voice and face.
These things became distinct disciplines that focus on finding solutions to problems of real life.
AI systems are now widely used in the fields of economics, medicine, engineering and warfare, and are also embedded in some home computers and video game software applications.
Excursions are an important part of any teaching. Quite often a teacher would like to take his students to places not accessible by bus.
Technology provides a solution in the form of virtual field trips. Students can see museum artifacts, visit an aquarium or admire beautiful art, all while sitting in their classroom.
Conducting a virtual tour is another great way to consider a trip and to share experiences with future classes.
For example, each year students of Bennet School in North Carolina produce a website about their trip to the state capital, each year a new version of the website is created, but the old versions remain accessible to use as an album.
Blogs can also help improve writing skills in students. While students often begin their blogging experience with poor grammar and spelling, the presence of an audience generally changes that.
Since students are often the most critical audience, the blogger will strive to improve his writing to avoid criticism.
Blogging also makes students more aware of the world around them. The need to feed the interest of the public inspires students to be wise and interesting (Toto, 2004).
Blogging is a tool that inspires collaboration and encourages students to expand their learning beyond the traditional school day.
Appropriate use of blogs can enable students to become more analytical and critical; actively responding to online materials, students can define their positions in the context of other writing and also sketch their own point of view on certain issues (Oravec, 2002).
Ottawa is a bilingual capital city of Canada and it has a number of art galleries and museums that display the history and present of Canada.
More to the south lies the Niagara Falls and to the north is home to the untouched natural beauty of Muskoka and beyond.
These and other things highlight Ontarians as what outsiders consider to be quintessentially Canadian.
Large areas to the north are sparsely populated, some are almost completely uninhabited wilderness.
