The islands of East Africa are situated on the Indian Ocean, along the eastern coast of Africa.
Madagascar is the largest island and, in terms of fauna, an independent continent.
The majority of the smaller islands are independent nations or associated with France, and are known as overseas departments.
The Arabs also introduced Islam to the region and it has become deeply rooted in the Comoros and Mayotte.
The influence and colonialism of Europe began in the 15th century, when the explorer Vasco da Gama of Portugal initiated the Cape route from Europe to India.
The region is bounded by the Sahara to the north and the Atlantic to the south and west.
Women: It is recommended that all female travelers declare themselves to be married, regardless of their actual marital status.
It is also good to have a ring (but not one that looks too expensive).
Women need to know that cultural differences can result in what would be considered harassment, and is not uncommon to be followed, held by the arm, etc.
Be firm when you disagree with men and don't be afraid to say no (no matter how small the issue, or cultural, or whatever, a difference is not to be tolerated).
Modern-day Casablanca was founded by Berber fishermen in the 10th century BC, and was used by the Phoenicians, Romans and Vandals as a strategic port called Anfa.
Destroyed by the Portuguese, it was rebuilt by them with the name Casa Branca, but they left after the earthquake of 1755.
The city was rebuilt by the Sultan of Morocco under the name Daru l-Badya and the Spanish merchants who established trade posts there called it Casablanca.
As for shopping, Casablanca is one of the most boring places in Morocco.
Around the old city center, you can find traditional Moroccan goods, such as tazinas, ceramics, leather goods, nargilehs and a wide range of handicrafts, but it's all for tourists.
Goma is a city in the Democratic Republic of the Congo in the far east near Rwanda.
In 2002, Nyiragongo destroyed Goma, covering most of the city with its lava.
Goma offers a certain level of security, but one must be informed of all movements outside of it to know the state of the battles that are still taking place in North Kivu province.
The city is also the base for climbing the Nyiragongo volcano, as well as the most affordable tracking of mountain gorillas in Africa.
You can use a bodaboda (motorcycle taxi) to get to the town. The normal (local) fare is around 5000 Ksh for the short trip.
Besides its relative inaccessibility, Timbuktu has been used as a metaphor for exotic and distant lands.
Timbuktu is a poor city, but it has a good reputation and a small airport.
In 1990 it was inscribed in the red list of world heritage due to the threat posed by the desert sands.
It was one of the key stops during the PBS program Wonders of the African World by Henry Louis Gates.
The city is very different from the rest of the country, as it has a style more Arab than African.
The Kruger National Park (KNP) is in northeastern South Africa and runs along the border with Mozambique, north to Zimbabwe and south to the Crocodile River.
The park covers an area of 19,500 km2 (7,500 sq mi) and is divided into 14 separate ecoregions, each of which supports a unique fauna.
It is one of the most important attractions in South Africa and is considered the most symbolic among the South African National Parks (SANParks).
Like all South African National Parks, there are day entrance fees for the park.
It's also worth buying a Wild Card, which gives access to either selected parks in South Africa, or all South African National Parks.
The Hong Kong Island gives the territory its name and is the location that many tourists regard as the most interesting.
The line of buildings that create the Hong Kong skyline is often compared to a glittering histogram, standing out against the waters of Victoria Harbour.
For the best views of Hong Kong, leave the island and cross into the Kowloon peninsula, which is situated on the mainland.
The vast majority of the urban development of Hong Kong Island is densely concentrated on land reclaimed from the sea at the northern shore.
This is the place which the British colonists took to themselves, and therefore, if one is seeking proof of the colonial past of the territory, here is a convenient place to look.
Sundarbans is the largest mangrove forest in the world, stretching 80 km (50 miles) into the sea.
The Sundarbans was declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO. The part of the forest in the Indian territory is called Sundarbans National Park.
The forest, however, is not just a mangrove swamp.
The Sundarbans covers an area of 3,850 square kilometres (1,485 sq mi), of which one-third is water or marsh.
In 1966, the Sundarbans was declared a wildlife sanctuary and there are estimated to be around 400 Bengal tigers and 30,000 spotted deer in the area.
Buses run from the inter-district bus station (across the river) all day, but the majority run between 6:30 and 7:30, especially those going west to Jakar or Bumthang.
Since the inter-district buses are often crowded, it is advisable to buy a ticket a few days in advance.
The majority of the districts are connected by small Japanese Coaster buses, which are comfortable and strong.
Common taxis are quick and comfortable ways to get to nearby locations, such as Paro (150 Nu) and Punakha (200 Nu).
The Oyapock River Bridge is a steel bridge. It spans the Oyapock River, connecting the cities of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges-de-l'Oyapock in French Guiana.
The two towers are 83 meters high, it is 378 meters wide and it has two corridors 3.50 m wide.
The vertical below the bridge is 15 metres (49 ft) high. Construction was completed in August 2011, but it did not open to traffic until March 2017.
It is planned that the bridge will be fully operational by September 2017, when it is expected to be completed with the Brazilian customs border crossings.
The Guarani were the most prominent indigenous group living in the area that is now eastern Paraguay, living as semi-nomadic hunters, who also practiced subsistence agriculture.
The Chaco region was also inhabited by other groups of indigenous peoples, such as the Guaycurú and Payaguá, who lived by hunting, gathering and fishing.
In the 16th century, Paraguay, previously known as the "Great Province of the Indians", was formed as a result of the meeting of Spanish conquerors and the indigenous groups.
The Spanish began a period of colonization that would last for three centuries.
Since its founding in 1537, Paraguay has maintained a great deal of its indigenous character and identity.
Argentina is well known for its football teams and players being among the best in the world.
The most important tournament of the year takes place in December in the polo fields of Las Cañitas.
You can also see smaller tournaments and games in other times of the year.
