The official currency of the Falkland Islands is the Falkland Islands pound (FKP), whose value is pegged to the British pound (GBP).
Money can be changed in the only bank on the islands, which is located in front of the FIC West shop in Stanley.
Pounds Sterling are widely accepted on the island and credit cards and US dollars are also widely accepted in Stanley.
On the outer islands you probably won't be able to use credit cards, but you can exchange money for pounds or US dollars; ask first to see which payment methods are accepted.
Since it is almost impossible to exchange Falkland Islands currency outside of the islands, change money before leaving.
Since Montevideo is located south of the equator, summer occurs when it is winter in the Northern Hemisphere and vice versa.
Montevideo is in the subtropics; in the summer months, temperatures usually exceed 30 °C (86 °F).
Winters can be deceptively cold: the temperature rarely drops below freezing, but the wind and humidity combine to make it feel colder than the thermometer indicates.
There are no distinct "wet" and "dry" seasons: the rainfall is nearly the same throughout the year.
Many of the animals of the park have grown accustomed to the presence of humans, but they are still wild animals and should not be fed or disturbed.
Park authorities request that you keep at least 100 yards/meters away from bears and wolves and 25 yards/meters from all other wildlife.
Regardless of how peaceful they look, the bison, elk, deer, bears, and almost all wildlife can be dangerous.
Every year, dozens of visitors are injured because they didn't keep a safe distance. Because these animals are big, wild and potentially dangerous, keep their space.
Also, be aware that odors attract bears and other wildlife, and avoid carrying or cooking food with strong odors and keep the campsite clean.
The city of Apia, the capital of Samoa, is located on the island of Upolu and has a population of less than 40,000 people.
Apiri was founded in the 1850s and became the capital of Samoa in 1959.
The harbor was the scene of the infamous naval standoff in 1889, when seven ships from Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom refused to leave the harbor.
All ships were sunk, with the exception of one British cruiser.
In the drive for independence, which was led by the Mau movement, a peaceful meeting at the city resulted in the death of paramount chief Tupua Tamasese Lealofi III.
Aukland has many beaches thanks to its location between two ports.
The beaches of North Shore (in the North Shore District) are on the Pacific Ocean and extend from Long Bay in the north to Devonport in the south.
Almost all of the beaches are sandy and safe for swimming, and most have shade from pohutukawa trees.
Tamaki Drive beaches are at the Waitemata Harbour in the affluent suburbs of Mission Bay and St Heliers in Central Auckland.
They are occasionally peopled family beaches where shops line the shore. Swimming is safe.
The main local beer is Number One. It is not a complex beer, but it is pleasant and refreshing. The other local beer is called Manta.
There are many drinkable wines from France, but wines from New Zealand and Australia may be better.
It is perfectly safe to drink the local tap water, but bottled water is easily available if you have any concerns.
To Australians, the concept of a “flat white” is alien. Espresso is “short black”, cappuccino is topped with a thick froth (not foam), and tea is drunk without milk.
The warm chocolate meets the standards of Belgium. The chocolate is expensive but great.
